4c5.7 0 10.3-4.6 10.3-10.3V18.5c0-1.6-.7-3.1-1.8-4.1-.5-.4-1.2 0-1.2.6z"></path></svg></div></div></div></a></div><div class="x1lliihq x1n2onr6 xh8yej3 x4gyw5p x14z9mp xhe4ym4 xaudc5v x1j53mea"><a class="x1i10hfl xjbqb8w x1ejq31n x18oe1m7 x1sy0etr xstzfhl x972fbf x10w94by x1qhh985 x14e42zd x9f619 x1ypdohk xt0psk2 x3ct3a4 xdj266r x14z9mp xat24cr x1lziwak xexx8yu xyri2b x18d9i69 x1c1uobl x16tdsg8 x1hl2dhg xggy1nq x1a2a7pz _a6hd" href="/atelierjolieofficial/p/DXXN5FcgB-E/" role="link" tabindex="0"><div class="_aagu"><div style="padding-bottom:133.33333333333331%" class="_aagv"><img alt="Atelier Jolie welcomed Chef Lebjulet with @eatoffbeat for a sold out dinner and demonstration in the Eat Offbeat Café that brought our guests and neighbors into the heart of Venezuelan culture. 

Chef Lebjulet is a Venezuelan-born culinary artist, educator, and storyteller who has called New York home for the past eight years. Before moving to the U.S., she was a professor in Mechanical Engineering, bringing precision, creativity, and discipline into her culinary work. She leads her own venture, Juliette’s Bakery, an online bakery where she continues to bring Venezuelan traditions to life through desserts and baked goods rooted in memory, heritage, and care. Raised in a culture where food is deeply tied to family and community, Lebjulet learned to cook alongside her loved ones, participating in traditions like communal tomato sauce-making a celebration of togetherness and heritage. Through her work, she shares the warmth and hospitality of Venezuela, using food as a way to connect people, celebrate culture, and create a sense of belonging. Chef Lebjulet has been collaborating with @eatoffbeat since 2019, sharing her culture and flavors through thoughtfully crafted dishes and experiences. 

To attend a dinner and demonstration, please visit the link in our bio for a full schedule of offerings. 

