#AtelierJolie #CatharsisArtsFoundation" class="x5yr21d xu96u03 x10l6tqk x13vifvy x87ps6o xh8yej3" crossorigin="anonymous" src="https://instagram.fblr22-2.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.82787-15/670431362_18003753725911906_8892302252583608541_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_e35_tt6&amp;_nc_cat=110&amp;ig_cache_key=Mzg3NzM3MDMwNjMzOTMzMDU3Ng%3D%3D.3-ccb7-5&amp;ccb=7-5&amp;_nc_sid=58cdad&amp;efg=eyJ2ZW5jb2RlX3RhZyI6InhwaWRzLjE0NDB4OTYwLnNkci5DMyJ9&amp;_nc_ohc=6wHb4FczvcgQ7kNvwFNOpXm&amp;_nc_oc=AdorjHPhrROBcc5aPdX4fk0LPFvLByriUiA1CnipbX2L7RFGYhsUDE7vAyNNLn6WEbRjbQ3y5RBZnVWhOW-nBuoa&amp;_nc_ad=z-m&amp;_nc_cid=0&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;_nc_ht=instagram.fblr22-2.fna&amp;_nc_gid=KhcTJbaPmf4R6u-jWLsrkQ&amp;_nc_ss=7a22e&amp;oh=00_Af3DztXdIGw9lsmRzeo9MZuRSiiMPeItmYrNgJo3ZMk_-g&amp;oe=69F892FD" style="object-fit:cover;visibility:hidden"/></div><div class="x1ey2m1c xtijo5x x1o0tod x10l6tqk x13vifvy"></div></div><div class="html-div xdj266r x14z9mp xat24cr x1lziwak xexx8yu xyri2b x18d9i69 x1c1uobl x9f619 xjbqb8w x78zum5 x15mokao x1ga7v0g x16uus16 xbiv7yw x1uhb9sk x1plvlek xryxfnj x1c4vz4f x2lah0s xdt5ytf xqjyukv x1qjc9v5 x1oa3qoh x1nhvcw1"></div></a></div><div class="x1lliihq x1n2onr6 xh8yej3 x4gyw5p x14z9mp xhe4ym4 xaudc5v x1j53mea"><a class="x1i10hfl xjbqb8w x1ejq31n x18oe1m7 x1sy0etr xstzfhl x972fbf x10w94by x1qhh985 x14e42zd x9f619 x1ypdohk xt0psk2 x3ct3a4 xdj266r x14z9mp xat24cr x1lziwak xexx8yu xyri2b x18d9i69 x1c1uobl x16tdsg8 x1hl2dhg xggy1nq x1a2a7pz _a6hd" href="/atelierjolieofficial/p/DXHlxqkAFrS/" role="link" tabindex="0"><div class="_aagu"><div style="padding-bottom:133.33333333333331%" class="_aagv"><img alt="Atelier Jolie, in collaboration with @catharsisartsfoundation, welcomes artist @pantehart this Saturday, April 18 for an afternoon of art and intimate conversation. 

Abareshi will read from texts drawn from their lived experience as a disabled subject, tracing the intimate dynamic between lover and caregiver. @pantehart’s practice contends with the realities of living in a Sick/Disabled body, shaped in part by sickle cell zero beta thalassemia. Through writing, performance, sculpture, video, and more, they push the body to and beyond its limits, interrogating the able-bodied gaze and confronting questions of consent, power, objectification, and care. Their work engages broader experiences of fragility, pain, sexuality, and mortality.

The readings will be presented with the video work Prescribed Regimen, functioning as both a visual and auditory poem, presented from the perspective of the caregiver.

The performance will be followed by a roundtable discussion, guided by cultural producer and longtime collaborator @kelseybennett333. 

All guests are welcome from 3:00-6:00pm on April 18 at 57 Great Jones Street.

